metadata.description:
ðŸŸ¢ã€°Storylineã€°ðŸŸ¢

Once upon a time, a God had a little daughter. The daughter liked to explore the planets on his father's cosmos. Suddenly the daughter got sick and died like a collapsing star. God gets alone, angry, depressed and finally mad. He turned all the universe to ash and mixed the ash of her daughter's soul with it to make her alive, But he failed. In the end, he decided to destroy himself to make a New cosmos of all generative planets from ash of himself and his daughter's soul to one more time in the eternity they can be with each other in a heart of a planet. If you listen carefully to the planets, you may hear them calling each other.

metadata.name: Noisy Gardens #97
metadata.description:
I had a wonderful childhood. I grew up near a big lake, in a house with a huge garden. You could get lost for the whole day, building houses on trees, collecting flowers and stones or stealing food from the vegetable garden. Having a brother of the same age made things even better, endless adventures with somebody saving you every time you are too dumb to realize you are walking into troubles.

We enjoyed the summers with the hot days, the fireflies and the nights full of falling stars. The winters with the snow, the stalactites and our box turtle disappearing for months to then reappear in the spring (Until she did not).

At the same time, taking care of the garden was a big responsibility, affecting our family life in many ways. Numerous times, I felt like the efforts we were putting in to keep it in order were never enough and nature was always faster in restoring her point of view. A struggle that affects us humans since we started to bend nature at our will, thousands of years ago.

In my gardens, I tried to capture this struggle, this constant fight to shape nature at our will.
However, I also tried to represent the beauty that can be found in both savage and human shaped nature, if shaped with love and respect.

I dedicate this project to my grandfather, who gave us a garden.
I am sure he would have loved it.

---

Hand coded with love and obsession. ðŸ’š

Powered by p5, p5.createLoop and chroma.

======> COMMANDS (In Live Mode) <======

Press â€˜sâ€™ to save the current output.
Press â€˜mâ€™ to open a menu with the available outputs.

The generation of a hi-res image, up to 8000x8000, takes a few seconds.
The generation of an Animated GIF takes several minutes and the save command works only once the GIF is complete.

Settings are passed as URL parameters that can be used to load different configurations.

- mode = 0 | 1
0 For static PNG images, 1 for animated GIFs

- size = s | m | l
The Size of the output, 1080x1080, 4000x4000, 8000x8000 for static images and 512x512, 800x800, 1080x1080 for animated GIFs

- fps = 10 | 15 | 20 | 25 | 30
Frames per second of animated GIFs

metadata.name: Sparsely Populated Grid #40
metadata.description:
â€œSparsely Populated Gridâ€ is the result of an architectâ€™s fascination with Cartographies and a crypto-enthusiast love for Neo Punk aesthetics. The first sketch, drawn by hand with Procreate, was made in October 2021.

This is an exploration on the field of Generative Cartographies, an abstract diagrammatic representation of a randomly generated area within the virtual IPFS world. Everything starts with an GRID of varying sizes and angles, subsequently POPULATED by a random number of forms. But, how to populate the grid? SPARSELY, of course, with just the right amount of superpositions.

The algorithm produces varying compositions of fourteen different forms, with seven possible mixes and ten colour palettes. Movement, made possible by its generative digital nature, follows sinusoidal patterns, as if the forms breathed and danced to an unheard music.

Besides, they never forget to celebrate birthdays.


// INTERACTIVITY

- CLICK or SPACEBAR to stop movement.
- UP and DOWN ARROWS to Disable/Enable graphic elements such as texts (wink).
- LEFT and RIGHT ARROWS (when stopped) to Move frames back and forth.
- Press 1 for a low-res PNG.
- Press 2 for a medium-res PNG (3x).
- Press 3 for a hi-res PNG (6x).
- Press G for Glitch (low-res).
- Press P for PixelArt (low-res).

If you want a different resolution, you can also add ?&res=xxx to the url to get your desired output. Then simply Right-Click SAVE the canvas -- experimental

metadata.name: adrift #21
metadata.description:
Take your entire life, full as it is with the vastness of your lived experiences â€“ and shape it into your cupped hands. Cherish this mesmerising world of yours as you would a ripe summer fruit, and behold at a glance its delicate yet dynamic balance â€” one change here or there, no matter how microscopic, affects the entire course of your world. 

How will you receive this world â€“ its situations that overwhelm, its sights that awe, the catastrophes, the serenity, its steadfast commitment to the present? Will you look upon all of us here, adrift and fragile together, with love?


Adrift is a project that reminds us to make peace with our world â€“ with all worlds â€“ by stepping back to make space for an all-encompassing perspective.


------------


Created by Jacek Markusiewicz @jMarkusiewicz
Creative collaboration with Tender @tender_art

Click on the image for resolution options and to save a .png file. Saving higher resolutions may not work in some browsers; in these cases, right-click-save the image. All drawing and geometric methods are written by mrkswcz using javascript, except for the following:

The pseudorandom terrain generation uses Hydraulic-Erosion by Sebastian Lague, inspired by "Reconnaissance" by TENDER x Nat Sarkissian (MIT License).

For finding paths that simulate connections in terrain and potential locations of cities, a C# script was adapted from the article "Pathfinding Algorithms in C#" by Kristian Ekman published in Code Project licensed under The Code Project Open License (CPOL). The code was translated to javascript and simplified for performance.

Many pseudorandom effects are achieved with perlin-simplex by David Guttman and seedrandom by David Bau (both MIT Licenses)

For more information, please see the bundle.js.LICENSE.txt file included in the package.

The "heat death" event is a small tribute to lunarean's fxhash project. The code that generates the disintegration effect interprets a fragment of lunarean's code. Further contributions are its adaptation for 3d transformations and its recursive character that modifies certain parameters over time.

The project uses CPU for calculations and rendering â€“ generating the image requires up to 500MB of free RAM. Testing was performed across browsers and devices, but please make sure it works on your device before minting. Note that there are minor colour-intensity differences between different browsers.

metadata.name: Irregular #113
metadata.description:
Irregular is a generative art project made to loop without an end.
Each iteration creates a random noise distributed grid of points. This base grid is the final static output image. Once created, it enters a deformation loop based on a flow movement, which is distorted and returns to the origin with a breathing rhythm.

Responsive, zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

Made with love, javascript and p5js
2022 Diego Pintos, see LICENSE.md

metadata.name: Petri 1500 v2 QHD  #724
metadata.description:
Petri 1500 is a celebration of reaching 1500 Twitter followers.
As I've grown as an artist what represents that growth but a petri dish, filled with life, finding a way.

There is a bug in the original version that cause display issues on retina & QHD displays. So this version fixes that, is free to all that held a copy at 00:30 14-09-2022 and a few spares for luck.

A sillybration of all things fx(hash) featuring some of my recognisable pallets and primatives
along with something new to me - noise and 'realistic' nature sketches.
All mashed for pure fun.

L to download 1000x1000
S to download 4000x4000
H to download 8000x8000

metadata.name: Planetx #21
metadata.description:
"Reason and emotion are two planetx that do not inhabit
the same moon. You know your pain is surmountable,
you know that tomorrow you will find a new love,
you know you are lucky to have health, family,
a roof to live in, but you don't feel that way.
And the feeling is powerful. Command us.
And people succumb. Like a plane falling from the sky,
taken hostage to an assault on the heart."
